    biography: `Overview
   Socrates was a classical Greek philosopher credited as one of the founders of Western philosophy. He is best known for his method of questioning, his ethical focus, and his martyr-like death, which had a profound influence on subsequent philosophical thought. Unlike many philosophers, Socrates wrote nothing himself; what we know about him comes mainly through the works of his students, especially Plato and Xenophon, and the playwright Aristophanes.
   
   Early Life
   Birthplace: Athens, Greece
   Parents: Sophroniscus (a stonemason) and Phaenarete (a midwife)
   Education: Socrates received a traditional Greek education in music, gymnastics, and grammar. Later, he developed a deep interest in philosophy, rhetoric, and natural science.
   He likely followed his father's profession for a time, but soon dedicated himself entirely to philosophy.
   Appearance and Personality
   Socrates was famously unattractive by classical standards: short, stocky, with bulging eyes and a snub nose. Yet he was known for his charisma, wit, and penetrating intellect. He was physically robust, known to withstand hunger, cold, and hardship with ease.
   He lived modestly, going barefoot and wearing the same clothes year-round. He valued virtue and wisdom over wealth and comfort.
   Philosophical Method
   The Socratic Method
   His most famous contribution to philosophy is the Socratic Method, a form of cooperative argumentative dialogue based on asking and answering questions to stimulate critical thinking and draw out underlying assumptions.
   This method sought to:
   Expose contradictions in someone’s beliefs
   Clarify concepts like justice, virtue, courage, and piety
   Encourage self-examination and intellectual humility
   Socrates believed that "the unexamined life is not worth living."
   Ethics and Beliefs
   Socrates focused on ethics and how people should live, rather than cosmology or metaphysics. He believed:
   Virtue is knowledge: to know the good is to do the good.
   No one does wrong willingly; wrongdoing stems from ignorance.
   The soul is more important than the body; we must care for our soul through moral living.
   He denied being a teacher but saw himself as a "midwife" helping others give birth to ideas.
   He did not offer a system of doctrines but rather challenged others to think for themselves.
   Influence on Others
   His most famous student was Plato, who would go on to teach Aristotle. Through Plato’s dialogues, Socrates became a foundational figure in Western philosophy.
   Plato portrayed Socrates as a near-saintly figure, a moral hero unafraid to die for truth and justice.
   
   Trial and Death
   In 399 BCE, at around 70 years old, Socrates was put on trial in Athens on charges of:
   Corrupting the youth
   Impiety (not believing in the gods of the city)
   He defended himself in court with composure, refusing to beg for his life. In his famous speech (recounted in Plato’s Apology), he claimed he was a “gadfly” sent by the gods to stir the Athenian state to self-reflection.
   He was found guilty and sentenced to death by drinking hemlock, a poisonous plant. Socrates calmly accepted his fate, surrounded by friends, in what became one of the most famous deaths in history.
   Legacy
   Socrates’ ideas and way of life laid the groundwork for Western ethical philosophy. Though he left no writings, his legacy has endured for over 2,400 years through:
   The Socratic method, still used in legal and philosophical education|
   His commitment to truth, reason, and personal integrity
   The vast body of Platonic dialogues in which he stars
   He is remembered as a martyr for philosophy, a man who chose death over abandoning his pursuit of truth and virtue. `,
