    shortStory: ` The Story of Socrates
   The Man Who Asked Why
   A long time ago, in ancient Athens, lived a man named Socrates. He wasn't rich. He didn’t dress fancy or wear shoes. He didn’t write books or travel the world. But he became one of the most important thinkers who ever lived.
   Socrates didn’t teach in a school. Instead, he walked around the city, talking to people in the streets, in the markets, wherever he could find someone to chat with. He asked them questions—lots of them. Questions like:
   •	What is courage?
   •	What does it mean to be good?
   •	Can anyone truly be wise?
   He believed that the best way to learn was not by giving answers but by asking questions, especially hard ones. People started calling this the Socratic method—asking, digging, and discovering the truth together. But not everyone liked his questions.
   Some people thought he was annoying. Others thought he was dangerous. They said, “He’s confusing the young people. He doesn’t respect the gods!” So, when Socrates was around 70 years old, he was put on trial. In front of 500 Athenian citizens, he calmly defended himself, saying he only wanted people to think more deeply and live more wisely.Still, the jury found him guilty. He was given a choice: stop asking questions and go free, or be sentenced to death. Socrates chose death. He drank a cup of poison called hemlock, surrounded by his friends. He said goodbye without fear, believing it was better to die being true to his beliefs than to live in silence. And though he died that day, his words lived on. His student Plato wrote down the conversations they had, and through them, Socrates’ spirit of questioning still lives today—in classrooms, in courtrooms, and anywhere people dare to ask, “Why?”`,
