    shortStory: `The Story of Diderot
The Man Who Wanted to Share All Knowledge
In a quiet town in France, in 1713, a boy named Denis Diderot was born. His father was a skilled maker of knives and tools, and he hoped Denis would become a priest. But Denis had other dreams.
He loved to read. He loved questions. And more than anything, he wanted to understand the world.
When he grew up, Diderot moved to Paris, the city of ideas. He didn’t have much money, but he had a sharp mind and a deep hunger for knowledge. He became a writer, a thinker, and slowly, a philosopher. He wrote bold books about freedom, science, and the power of reason—books so daring that one of them landed him in prison.
But jail didn’t stop him. It only made him more determined.
Then one day, Diderot had a crazy idea:
What if there was a book that held all human knowledge—science, art, politics, medicine, mechanics, music, and more?
And not just for kings and priests, but for everyone?
So he started the Encyclopédie—a giant book of everything. He worked with dozens of thinkers and scientists. They wrote articles that explained how things worked, how to think, and how to question authority.
The Church and the King were furious. They tried to stop him. They banned the book. But Diderot kept going, editing in secret, hiding pages, smuggling volumes.
For over 20 years, he worked. And when the Encyclopédie was finally complete, it became one of the most powerful tools of the Enlightenment. It helped light the way to revolution, democracy, and modern science.
In his later years, Diderot wrote wild, playful books that explored free will, morality, and the meaning of life. Some were so daring, they weren’t published until after his death.
Though he never got rich, and wasn’t always famous, Denis Diderot believed that knowledge should be shared, freedom should be protected, and that ideas could change the world.
And he was right.`,

