    biography: `Overview
Dignāga was a 5th–6th century Indian Buddhist philosopher who revolutionized Indian logic, epistemology (the theory of knowledge), and the Buddhist scholastic tradition. He is considered the founder of Buddhist logic and epistemology (pramāṇa theory) and laid the groundwork for centuries of Buddhist and non-Buddhist debate and inquiry in India and beyond.
His most famous work, the Pramāṇa-samuccaya ("Compendium of Valid Cognition"), redefined how knowledge is understood and justified in Buddhist philosophy. He is also known for advancing Yogācāra-Madhyamaka thought.
Early Life and Background
Born: Around 480 CE in South India, possibly in the region of Kanchipuram or near Tamil Nadu
Language: Sanskrit
Religious Tradition: Mahayana Buddhism, aligned especially with the Yogācāra (Mind-Only) school, though influenced by Madhyamaka thought as well
Not much is known about Dignāga’s personal life, but records say he was originally trained in non-Buddhist logic (likely from the Nyāya school) and later studied under Vasubandhu, one of the great masters of Buddhist thought. He became a monk and scholar, eventually challenging and transforming major theories of reasoning, perception, and debate.
Philosophical Contributions
1. Pramāṇa Theory (Theory of Knowledge)
Dignāga’s core philosophical concern was:
How do we know what we know?
He claimed there are only two valid sources of knowledge (pramāṇas):
Perception (pratyakṣa) – direct, non-conceptual experience
Inference (anumāna) – reasoning based on valid signs
He rejected verbal testimony, analogy, and other sources used in Hindu logic systems, arguing they are reducible to perception or inference.
He wrote:
“There are only two means of valid knowledge: direct perception and inference.”
2. Theory of Perception
Perception is non-conceptual, momentary, and free from error.
As soon as conceptual thought arises, it overlays the raw data of perception with names, categories, and errors.
He emphasized that perception is always of particulars, while conceptual thought is of universals—and universals, for Dignāga, are mental constructs, not real things.
3. Theory of Inference
He developed a rigorous structure for valid inference, using hetu (reasons), pakṣa (subject), and sādhya (predicate).
His logic aimed to defeat non-Buddhist schools in debate and sharpen the tools of Buddhist scholarship.
He created the famous “Wheel of Reasoning” (Hetucakra)—a model for evaluating the correctness of inferential arguments.
Major Works
Pramāṇa-samuccaya – His magnum opus, where he systematically lays out his theories of perception and inference
Nyāyamukha – A summary of logical reasoning, widely studied and translated
Ālambana-parīkṣā – A critique of external object theory
Hetucakra-ḍamaru – A text explaining the structure of valid reasoning
Trikāla-parīkṣā – Treatise on temporal logic
Commentaries – He also commented on Vasubandhu’s works and earlier Yogācāra texts
Influence and Legacy
Dignāga’s influence was immense, both within and outside Buddhism:
Buddhist Philosophy:
He transformed Buddhist scholasticism by introducing formal logic and epistemology into scriptural interpretation.
He inspired a new Buddhist logical tradition, carried forward and systematized by Dharmakīrti, who became his most famous intellectual successor.
His ideas were foundational to later Tibetan Buddhist scholasticism, especially in the Gelug school led by Tsongkhapa.
Beyond Buddhism:
Hindu philosophers of the Nyāya and Mīmāṃsā schools engaged with and critiqued Dignāga’s arguments for centuries.
Jain thinkers, too, responded to his theories in the context of inter-traditional debates.
Transmission:
His works were translated into Tibetan, Chinese, and other languages.
His influence spread to Tibet, China, and East Asia, shaping Mahayana Buddhist logic and debate traditions.
Death
Dignāga likely died around 540 CE, having spent much of his life in teaching and writing.
Exact details about his death are unknown, as are many biographical details, but his philosophical legacy lived on for over 1,500 years.
Legacy Summary
Dignāga:
Founded the Buddhist school of logic and epistemology
Argued that valid knowledge arises only from direct perception and inference
Sharpened Buddhist philosophy into a powerful, analytical tradition
Influenced not only Buddhist schools, but Hindu and Jain philosophy as well
Inspired generations of scholars, especially Dharmakīrti and Tibetan thinkers
He stands as one of the greatest minds of Indian philosophy, alongside figures like Nāgārjuna, Śaṅkara, and Udayana.`,
    shortStory: `The Story of Dignāga
The Monk Who Wanted to Know How We Know
Long ago in ancient India, around the 5th century, a quiet and brilliant boy was born in the south. His name was Dignāga. From an early age, he didn’t just want to know what was true—he wanted to know how we know it’s true.
Dignāga grew up asking big questions:
How do we see the world?
Can we trust what we think?
What is real, and what is just in the mind?
He became a Buddhist monk, studying with wise teachers, including the great Vasubandhu. But Dignāga didn’t simply accept what he heard—he tested every idea, questioned every assumption. He studied the great Hindu logic traditions, mastered debate, and then did something amazing:
He created a new system of Buddhist logic.
He said: “There are only two true ways to know something:
Perception—what we see and feel directly,
and Inference—what we figure out through careful reasoning.”
He showed how perception is always about the present moment, the raw detail before words interfere. And how inference lets us understand things we can’t see—like fire from smoke, or kindness from a quiet act.
He built a wheel of reasoning, the Hetucakra, and taught monks how to debate—not to win, but to search for clarity.
Some people were amazed. Others were confused. But slowly, Buddhist schools began to change. His ideas helped turn Buddhism into a sharp, logical, living tradition—one that could stand up to any challenge.
Dignāga spent his life writing, teaching, and thinking. His works traveled far—across India, into Tibet, and into the great monasteries of China. Even after he passed away, his questions kept echoing:,
What can we know? How do we know it? And how can we tell the difference between truth and illusion?`,

