    biography: `Overview
Rāmānuja was a revered Hindu theologian, philosopher, and social reformer, who offered a profound interpretation of the Vedānta that affirmed the unity of God and soul, but with important distinctions. His philosophy, known as Viśiṣṭādvaita Vedānta (qualified non-dualism), emphasized devotion (bhakti) to Vishnu and Śrī, personal connection to God, and the eternal reality of the soul and world as parts of the divine.
Rāmānuja challenged the earlier Advaita (non-dual) philosophy of Śaṅkara, which claimed the world and soul were ultimately illusion (māyā). Instead, Rāmānuja taught that God (Nārāyaṇa/Vishnu) is the only Supreme Reality, but souls and the universe are real and exist within Him, like body within a soul.
Early Life and Education
Born: c. 1017 CE in Śrīperumbudur, Tamil Nadu, India
Caste: Brāhmaṇa (Brahmin) family
Name at birth: Rāmānuja (meaning “younger brother of Rāma”)
Teachers: Initially studied under Yādava Prakāśa, an Advaita philosopher
Even as a young man, Rāmānuja was known for his brilliance, kindness, and independent thinking. While studying Advaita Vedānta, he disagreed with the idea that the soul and world are ultimately unreal. His conflicts with his teacher led him to seek a new understanding of the scriptures.
He later became a disciple of Yāmuna, a Viśiṣṭādvaita teacher, though Yāmuna passed away before they met. Rāmānuja continued Yāmuna’s work and shaped Viśiṣṭādvaita into a complete philosophical and devotional system.
Viśiṣṭādvaita Vedānta (Qualified Non-Dualism)
Core Principles: God is One, but Has Qualities (Viśeṣaṇas):
Brahman is not without attributes; He is personal, gracious, and loving.
Vishnu (Nārāyaṇa) is the Supreme Being, possessing infinite qualities and the source of all existence.
Soul and World Are Real and Dependent:
Individual souls (jīvas) and the universe are real, eternal, and distinct from Brahman—but not separate.
They are like body and soul: the universe and souls are the body, and God is the inner Self.
Bhakti (Devotion) is the Path to Liberation:
Through loving devotion, surrender, and grace, the soul can attain mokṣa (liberation).
Surrender to Vishnu (prapatti) is the highest path, accessible to all, regardless of caste.
Mokṣa is Union with God, Not Absorption:
Unlike Śaṅkara’s Advaita, which teaches merging with Brahman, Rāmānuja taught that liberated souls retain individuality while living in blissful service of God.
Writings and Major Works
Rāmānuja wrote several important Sanskrit commentaries and philosophical treatises:
Śrī Bhāṣya – Commentary on Brahma Sūtras (his most famous work)
Vedārthasaṅgraha – Summary of Vedantic meaning; defends his view using Upaniṣads
Gītā Bhāṣya – Commentary on the Bhagavad Gītā
Vedānta Saṅgraha, Vedānta Dīpa – Additional philosophical texts
Religious and Social Contributions
1. Temple Reform and Devotion
Rāmānuja was a temple administrator at Śrīraṅgam, one of the holiest temples of Vishnu in South India. He:
Standardized temple rituals
Encouraged participation by all devotees, regardless of caste
Promoted Tamil devotional hymns (Divya Prabandham) alongside Sanskrit scriptures
2. Social Equality
Rāmānuja was ahead of his time in promoting spiritual equality, allowing lower castes to engage in worship and devotional practice. He challenged orthodoxy by teaching that God’s grace is for all beings.
3. Founding of the Śrīvaiṣṇava Tradition
He established the Śrīvaiṣṇava sect, which blended Vedāntic philosophy, ritual devotion, and social inclusivity. His teachings continue to guide the Śrīvaiṣṇava communities in South India and beyond.
Exile and Perseverance
Because of his inclusive reforms, Rāmānuja faced opposition from royalist Shaiva rulers. He was exiled from Śrīraṅgam for over a decade and took refuge in Melkote (Karnataka), where he continued to teach and convert many to the bhakti path.
He later returned to Śrīraṅgam, where he led the community for many years.
Death and Legacy
Died: c. 1137 CE at Śrīraṅgam, Tamil Nadu
His body is preserved and still worshipped in the Śrīraṅgam temple in a seated position
Legacy
Rāmānuja's legacy is vast and enduring:
Viśiṣṭādvaita Vedānta remains one of the three principal Vedāntic schools (along with Śaṅkara’s Advaita and Madhva’s Dvaita)
Inspired devotional bhakti movements across India
Champion of inclusive spiritual practice
Influenced later thinkers like Mahatma Gandhi, Swami Vivekananda, and Aurobindo
Revered as a saint, teacher, and visionary
In 2017, his 1000th birth anniversary (Sahasrabdi) was celebrated across India with national honors.`,
    shortStory: `The Story of Rāmānuja
The Sage of Loving Devotion
A thousand years ago, in a small village called Śrīperumbudur in South India, a bright child named Rāmānuja was born. From a young age, his eyes sparkled with questions—not just about the stars and scriptures, but about God, love, and the soul.
He studied with the best teachers and learned Vedānta, the deep philosophy hidden in the ancient Upanishads. But something troubled him.
His teacher said the world wasn’t real. That everything—souls, emotions, even devotion—was an illusion.
But Rāmānuja looked around and saw beauty, suffering, joy, and longing. He looked into the eyes of others and felt love. How could this all be false?
So he searched for a new path. He found it not just in logic, but in devotion (bhakti)—a deep, personal love for Vishnu, the gentle, all-loving God of the universe.
Rāmānuja began to teach:
“God is real. The world is real. Souls are real.
But everything belongs to God—
We are His body. He is our soul.”
He called this qualified non-dualism—we are one with God, yet still ourselves.
Not lost, but embraced.
He said that anyone, rich or poor, high caste or low, could reach God through sincere devotion. He opened temple doors to all. He welcomed everyone who came with a loving heart.
But not all agreed. Some powerful leaders disliked his bold ideas. They exiled him. He wandered from place to place, spreading kindness, teaching devotion, and gathering followers.
When he returned to Śrīraṅgam, the sacred city of Vishnu, he built a community where ritual, learning, and love worked together. He honored Tamil songs, Sanskrit texts, and the voices of saints who had come before him.
As an old man, he sat peacefully at the temple, eyes full of compassion. When he passed away, people said his spirit never left—and even today, his form is preserved there, seated in eternal stillness.
Rāmānuja didn’t try to erase the world. He tried to uplift it—by reminding us that to love God is to love the world, and that in surrender, we find freedom`,
