    biography: `Overview
Epicurus was an ancient Greek philosopher who founded the school of Epicureanism, one of the most influential schools of Hellenistic philosophy. Contrary to popular misunderstanding, he did not teach hedonistic indulgence, but rather that the highest good is a life of simple pleasures, wise choices, and freedom from fear and pain.
He offered a rational, secular philosophy, grounded in atomism, natural science, and ethics, and believed that understanding nature could help people live without anxiety, especially fear of death or the gods.
Early Life and Education
Born: 341 BCE on the island of Samos, a Greek settlement off the coast of Asia Minor
Family: Modest background; his father was a schoolteacher
At age 18, he moved to Athens for military service and became immersed in philosophy
He studied under Platonists and atomist philosophers, especially the ideas of Democritus, who taught that all things are made of atoms and void
Founding His School
After traveling and teaching in various cities, Epicurus returned to Athens and around 306 BCE founded his own school called The Garden (Kēpos)—so named because it was located in a private garden, unlike the more formal academies of Plato or Aristotle.
His school welcomed men and women, free people and slaves—an unusual and inclusive practice for the time. Students lived together in simplicity and friendship, following a peaceful and moderate lifestyle.
Core Teachings of Epicurus
1. Philosophy as Therapy
Epicurus believed that philosophy was not for abstract debate but for healing the soul. Its purpose was to help people live happy, fearless, and tranquil lives.
2. Pleasure is the Highest Good (But Not What You Think)
Pleasure (hēdonē) is the absence of pain and disturbance—not indulgence or luxury
True pleasure is found in peace of mind (ataraxia) and freedom from bodily pain (aponia)
He emphasized natural and necessary desires (like food, friendship, shelter), while warning against vain desires (like wealth, fame, power)
3. No Fear of Gods or Death
The gods may exist, but they do not intervene in human affairs
Death is nothing to fear:
“Death is nothing to us, for when we exist, death is not; and when death exists, we are not.”
Understanding the natural world removes fear and superstition
4. The Universe is Made of Atoms
All matter is composed of atoms and void, constantly in motion
There is no divine design, no eternal soul, and no fate—just natural causes
Free will arises from the “swerve”—a spontaneous deviation in the motion of atoms
Writings and Legacy
Epicurus was a prolific writer, authoring over 300 works, but most of his writings have been lost.
What remains:
Principal Doctrines (brief philosophical maxims)
Letter to Menoeceus (on ethics)
Letters to Herodotus and Pythocles (on physics and the cosmos)
Quotes preserved by later writers like Diogenes Laërtius and Lucretius
Epicurean Community
His school thrived in Athens and continued for several centuries. The Epicureans lived simply, valued friendship, and often stayed away from politics, believing it disrupted peace of mind.
Their motto could be summed up as:
“Live unnoticed” (lathe biōsas) – seek a quiet, modest, joyful life
Death and Personal Character
Died: 270 BCE at age 71, likely from complications due to kidney stones
His final days were marked by pain, which he bore calmly, writing letters to friends expressing gratitude for the joy he had found in life
He was deeply admired by his followers for his gentleness, clarity, and kindness
Legacy
Though misunderstood and often slandered by rivals (especially Stoics and Christians), Epicurus’ ideas profoundly influenced later thinkers:
Lucretius, a Roman poet, preserved his teachings in De Rerum Natura (On the Nature of Things)
Enlightenment philosophers such as Hume, Jefferson, and Bentham praised his rational ethics and secular worldview
Modern science aligns with his naturalist atomism, and modern philosophy echoes his emphasis on well-being and minimalism
Famous Quotes
“It is impossible to live a pleasant life without living wisely and honorably and justly.”
“Of all the things which wisdom provides to make life entirely happy, much the greatest is the possession of friendship.”
“He who is not satisfied with a little is satisfied with nothing.”`,
    shortStory: `The Story of Epicurus
The Philosopher of Simple Joys
A long time ago, on the green island of Samos, a quiet boy named Epicurus began to ask questions—not about the gods on Mount Olympus, but about life.
Why do people suffer?
Why do they fear death?
What makes a life truly happy?
He studied, traveled, and thought deeply. And when he returned to Athens, he didn’t build a temple or a monument—he opened a garden.
In this peaceful place, Epicurus welcomed anyone—women and men, free and enslaved—not with sermons, but with conversation, bread, and laughter.
He taught something very simple:
“Pleasure is the goal of life. But real pleasure is not indulgence—it is peace.”
Eat simply. Think clearly. Be kind.
Avoid pain, not by chasing wealth or fame, but by living modestly, wisely, and with friends.
He said:
Don’t fear death—it is only the end of feeling.
Don’t fear the gods—they are not watching you.
Don’t fear life—when you live simply, life is enough.
Epicurus lived quietly, with few possessions and many friends. He wrote hundreds of letters and sayings, always reminding his followers:
“He who has a little, and is content with it, is rich.”
Even when he grew ill and suffered great pain, he wrote to a friend:
“I am happy, remembering all our good times and the wisdom we shared.”
He died at peace, just as he had lived—calmly, joyfully, wisely.
And though his enemies misunderstood him, his garden kept growing—in hearts, in books, and in every quiet moment when someone chooses joy over fear.`,
