    biography: `Overview
Pythagoras was a Greek philosopher best known for the Pythagorean theorem, but his legacy extends far beyond mathematics. He founded a religious-philosophical school that combined mathematics, metaphysics, music, ethics, and spiritual purification.
To his followers, Pythagoras was more than a teacher—he was a prophet, a seer, and the founder of a way of life rooted in harmony, order, and the soul’s journey.
Because no writings by Pythagoras survive, much of what we know comes from later sources, often blending history with legend.
Early Life and Education
Born: c. 570 BCE on the island of Samos, in the Aegean Sea
Family: Belonged to an aristocratic family; his father was a gem-engraver or merchant
Traveled widely: Egypt, Babylon, Phoenicia, possibly even India
Studied with priests, sages, and mathematicians, absorbing knowledge of geometry, astronomy, and religion
His travels exposed him to a wide range of beliefs and symbols, many of which he would weave into his own teachings.
The Move to Croton and Founding of the School
Around 530 BCE, Pythagoras left Samos and settled in Croton (a Greek colony in southern Italy). There, he founded a community that was part school, part spiritual brotherhood, known as the Pythagoreans.
The Pythagorean school was:
Strictly communal—members lived together, gave up personal possessions, and followed strict rules of conduct
Secretive—initiates took vows of silence and secrecy; the inner teachings were reserved for the most devoted
Dual-purpose—focused on both scientific inquiry and spiritual purification
Core Teachings and Beliefs
1. Mathematics as Sacred
Pythagoras believed that numbers were the essence of all things
Everything in the universe could be explained through mathematical relationships
He is credited with the Pythagorean Theorem:
In a right triangle, the square of the hypotenuse equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides
(This theorem was known to the Babylonians earlier, but Pythagoras is believed to have offered a formal proof.)
2. Music and Harmony
He discovered that musical tones correspond to numerical ratios
This led to the idea that the universe itself is music—the “music of the spheres”, a cosmic harmony created by the motion of celestial bodies
Music was used as a form of healing and spiritual tuning
3. The Immortal Soul and Reincarnation
Pythagoras taught that the soul is immortal and passes through cycles of rebirth (metempsychosis)
The goal of life was to purify the soul through wisdom, ethics, and detachment
Followers practiced vegetarianism and abstained from violence to avoid harming any living soul
4. Ethical Life and Discipline
The Pythagoreans followed a code of ethical conduct—including honesty, self-control, silence, and harmony in all actions
They believed virtue and wisdom brought one closer to the divine
Mystical and Symbolic Beliefs
Pythagoras was fascinated by symbols such as the tetractys—a triangular figure made of ten points (1 + 2 + 3 + 4), representing harmony and the structure of the universe
He viewed mathematical order as a divine language
Death and Legacy
Died: Around 495 BCE, possibly in Metapontum, Italy
He may have died during political unrest that destroyed the Pythagorean community
After his death, his school split into different branches—some continued the mathematical tradition, others the mystical and ethical teachings
Historical Impact
Pythagoras influenced generations of thinkers in both science and spirituality:
Influence on Western Thought:
Inspired Plato, who also saw the universe as mathematically ordered
Precursor to mathematical physics and harmonic theory
Anticipated ideas about the interconnectedness of science, art, and soul
Legacy in Modern Culture:
Seen as a bridge between reason and mysticism
Revered in mathematics and geometry
Respected in esoteric and New Age traditions for his holistic worldview
Famous Sayings (Attributed to Pythagoras or His School)
“All is number.”
“Do not say a little in many words, but a great deal in a few.”
“As long as man continues to be the ruthless destroyer of lower living beings, he will never know health or peace.”`,
    shortStory: `The Story of Pythagoras
The Philosopher of Numbers and Stars
A long time ago, on the island of Samos, a boy named Pythagoras would sit beneath the stars, not just to admire them—but to listen. He believed the stars were singing, that the whole universe was humming with mathematical music, if only we could hear.
He traveled far and wide—Egypt, Babylon, perhaps even India—searching not for gold or glory, but for truth. He learned from priests and mystics, astronomers and sages. And wherever he went, he found one thing in common: numbers.
He saw that triangles held secrets, that music could be measured, and that the cosmos moved in perfect proportion. To Pythagoras, numbers weren’t just tools—they were divine.
In a city called Croton, he gathered students—not warriors, but seekers. Together they created The Garden, a place of silence, study, and shared bread. Men and women lived as equals, learning how to tune not just instruments, but their souls.
He taught that:
The soul is eternal and travels from body to body.
We must live pure, honest lives to free it.
Mathematics reveals the order behind chaos.
Even the planets moved to silent music—the harmony of the spheres.
Some said he could remember his past lives. Others said he could calm animals with his voice. His students whispered that he was not just a man—but a messenger of universal wisdom.
But not everyone understood.
His school was attacked, his followers scattered. Pythagoras died quietly, perhaps in exile. Yet his teachings echoed on.
And even today, in every right triangle, in every musical note, in every moment of peace when things feel in balance—Pythagoras still whispers:
“All is number. All is harmony. Live with reason, and you will live in tune with the cosmos.”`,
