    shortStory: `The Story of Karl Marx
The Man Who Challenged the World to Change
In a quiet German town in 1818, a boy named Karl Marx was born into a world of books and arguments. His father was a lawyer, his mother a storyteller, and young Karl was curious about why some people had so much—and others so little.
He grew up reading the great philosophers, questioning kings and priests, and dreaming not of riches, but of justice.
At university, he studied law and philosophy, but it was in the smoke-filled streets of Paris that he found his fire. There he met Friedrich Engels, a wealthy man who hated injustice as much as he did. Together, they would write words that would shake the world.
“Workers of the world, unite!” they declared in The Communist Manifesto.
Marx believed that history was not made by kings, but by struggle—the struggle between those who own and those who work. He saw how capitalism turned people into machines, and profits into gods.
So he wrote.
In dusty libraries and in cold London rooms, often too poor to feed his family, Marx poured his thoughts into his greatest work: Das Kapital—a deep, detailed map of the capitalist world, exposing how money moves, how power grows, and how the system feeds on inequality.
He didn’t ask people to follow him. He asked them to understand the world—and then change it.
He died in 1883, nearly forgotten.
But his words lived on.
They would light fires in factories and fields, inspire revolutions and reforms, and echo through the streets of the 20th century.
Some used his name to build freedom. Others, empires.
Some saw him as a prophet, others as a threat.
But no one could ignore the man who once said:
“The point is not to interpret the world, but to change it.”
And with a pen, Karl Marx changed it forever.`,
