    shortStory: `The Story of Al-Farabi
The Philosopher Who Dreamed of a Virtuous City
In a land of deserts and stars, where ancient wisdom met new faith, a boy was born in the city of Farab. His name was Abū Naṣr Al-Fārābī—and he would one day be called “The Second Teacher,” just after Aristotle.
He grew up speaking many tongues, learning from many lands. In Baghdad, where scrolls from Greece were translated into Arabic, young Al-Farabi sat with scholars, reading the words of Plato, Aristotle, and the Qur’an—not as strangers, but as parts of one great truth.
He believed reason and revelation were not rivals, but companions.
That the mind and soul could walk together, side by side.
He wrote of logic, to sharpen thought.
He wrote of music, to stir harmony.
And he dreamed of a city—not built from stone, but from virtue. A place where a philosopher-ruler would guide the people with wisdom, not force. Where truth would shine, even through symbols. Where the highest goal was not gold or power, but happiness through understanding.
He lived simply, wore little, and wandered through Baghdad, Aleppo, and Damascus, carrying nothing but his books and thoughts.
Some called him strange. Others, wise.
He taught quietly. He died quietly.
But his ideas echoed loudly—through the minds of Avicenna, Averroes, and Aquinas.
Because Al-Farabi showed the world that a just mind can light the way,
and that the greatest cities begin not with walls—
but with wisdom.`,
