    shortStory: `The Story of Avicenna
The Boy Who Carried the World in His Mind
Long ago, in the heart of Persia, a boy named Ibn Sina was born under a sky full of stars. Before he turned ten, he had memorized the Qur’an. By sixteen, he was curing patients no one else could heal. By eighteen, he was a royal physician, solving mysteries of the body with a mind sharper than any sword.
But he didn’t stop with medicine.
He read Aristotle, again and again, until its meaning opened like a flower in his hands. He asked questions others feared to ask:
“What is the soul?”
“What if I were suspended in air, with no body—would I still know I exist?”
He answered not with poetry, but with logic and science, building a system where reason and faith could walk side by side.
He wandered from city to city—sometimes honored, sometimes hunted—carrying nothing but books, ink, and his unquenchable thirst for truth.
He wrote hundreds of works, often by lantern light, sometimes dictating while on horseback, speaking of stars and cells, God and gravity, medicine and metaphysics.
In The Canon of Medicine, he laid out how to heal with observation and evidence, not superstition. In The Book of Healing, he explored the universe—from the heavens above to the mind within.
When he died in 1037, the world dimmed for a moment. But his name lived on.
Doctors studied him in Paris and Cairo. Philosophers quoted him in Baghdad and Oxford. And across centuries, his voice whispered to all who dare to ask,
“What is this world, and who am I within it?”
Because Avicenna believed that the mind is a lamp,
And every question we ask is a match waiting to be struck.`,
