    shortStory: `The Story of Patañjali
The Sage Who Stilled the Mind
Long ago, in a land where rivers curled like mantras across the earth, a child was born from the sky. Some say he descended like a falling prayer—a drop of light landing on a lotus leaf. His name was Patañjali.
He spoke little, but listened deeply. While others chased gods or gold, Patañjali watched the mind, its waves, its winds, its wandering. He saw that most suffering came not from the world—but from within. And he asked:
“What if the mind could be made still?”
So he sat.
And he studied.
And he wrote—not stories, but sūtras: short threads of truth.
He called it the Yoga Sūtras—a path of eight limbs to guide seekers from discipline to devotion, from breath to bliss, from movement to silence.
He taught that Yoga was not bending the body—but mastering the mind. That true freedom wasn’t out there—it was the still point within.
Some say he also gave grammar to language, and medicine to the sick.
Others say he had the lower body of a serpent—smooth, coiled, and wise.
But all agree:
Patañjali did not shout his truth.
He whispered it, in sutras, in breath, in stillness.
And for those who listen even now,
his voice still says:
“Yoga is the quieting of the mind’s chatter—so the soul can remember itself.”`,
