    shortStory: `The Story of Nāgārjuna
The Philosopher Who Found Freedom in Emptiness
Long ago, in the sun-warmed lands of South India, a curious boy named Nāgārjuna sat beneath trees and stared at the sky, not for answers—but for questions.
He became a monk, learned all the scriptures, debated with sharp minds, and studied truths carved into stone. But something was missing. The teachings felt solid, rigid, fixed—and yet life was anything but.
So he began to look deeper.
He saw that everything—thoughts, objects, selves, even truths—arose not alone, but in relation. A seed needs soil. A flame needs air. A self needs others. Nothing stands alone.
He called this śūnyatā—emptiness—not as a void, but as the freedom from false ideas of independence.
He taught the Middle Way: not clinging to what exists, nor falling into denial—but walking the narrow space where wisdom dissolves illusions.
He wrote in short verses, sharp as lightning:
“Things exist—not by their own nature, but because they depend on causes and conditions.”
Some feared his words. Others were freed by them.
He said: “Even emptiness is empty. Do not grasp it. Let go.”
And so he became the second Buddha to many—not because he gave new truths, but because he cleared the dust from the old ones.
Nāgārjuna left no temple, no empire, no monument.
Only a path.
A quiet path between extremes.
A path that points not to what is—but to how things appear, and how to be free among them.`,
