    biography: `Buddhist monk, philosopher, and author of Bodhicaryāvatāra (The Way of the Bodhisattva)
Overview
Śāntideva was an Indian Mahāyāna Buddhist monk and scholar who lived around the 8th century CE at Nālandā University, a renowned center of learning in ancient India. Though little is known about his life, he is revered for his masterpiece, the Bodhicaryāvatāra, a poetic guide to the bodhisattva path—the way of the awakened being who lives for the benefit of all.
He emphasized the unity of compassion (karuṇā) and wisdom (prajñā), offering some of the most powerful meditations on selflessness, patience, and universal responsibility in all of Buddhist literature.
Early Life and Background
Śāntideva’s early life is mostly shrouded in legend.
He is believed to have been born into a royal family, possibly in Saurāṣṭra (modern-day Gujarat, India), and was originally named Śantivarman.
He reportedly had a deep spiritual inclination and abandoned his princely life to become a monk.
He joined Nālandā Monastic University, the leading Buddhist university of the time, where he studied under Mahāyāna Buddhist teachers and became fully immersed in the bodhisattva ideal.
The Legend of the “Lazy Monk”At Nālandā, Śāntideva was known for his quiet and humble demeanor. Some of the other monks misunderstood his simplicity and accused him of being lazy and doing “nothing but eat and sleep.”
To test him, they invited him to give a public teaching, expecting him to fail. Śāntideva calmly accepted and asked, “Shall I teach something new or something familiar?”
The monks replied, “Something new.”
Then, seated before hundreds, Śāntideva spoke the Bodhicaryāvatāra—a spontaneous outpouring of compassion, wisdom, and poetic brilliance. It is said that as he reached the final chapters, he rose into the air and disappeared, leaving the audience in awe.
The Bodhicaryāvatāra (The Way of the Bodhisattva)
Śāntideva’s greatest work is the Bodhicaryāvatāra, a text still widely studied in Tibetan Buddhism and other Mahāyāna traditions.
It is a spiritual and ethical guide structured into ten chapters, describing the stages of the bodhisattva’s path, including:
The awakening of bodhicitta – the wish to attain enlightenment for the sake of all beings
Confession and purification
Commitment to practice
4–6. Vigilance, patience, effort
Joyful perseverance
Meditative concentration
Wisdom – the insight into emptiness (śūnyatā)
Dedication of merit to all beings
Key Teachings
Selflessness: There is no fixed “I”—all suffering stems from self-clinging
Compassion: One should exchange self-interest for the welfare of others
Patience: The greatest strength is the ability to endure suffering without anger
Wisdom: All phenomena are empty of inherent existence; only through insight can true liberation arise
Bodhicitta: The heart of a bodhisattva lies in universal compassion and the wish to relieve all suffering
Other WorksŚāntideva is also attributed with a second text:
Śikṣāsamuccaya (The Compendium of Teachings) – A scholarly compilation of sūtra passages with commentary, highlighting the bodhisattva's ethical discipline and practice
This text shows his deep scriptural knowledge and commitment to the Mahayana ethical life.
Philosophical Importance
Śāntideva’s writings became especially central to:
Tibetan Buddhism, particularly the Gelug school founded by Tsongkhapa
The practice of lojong (mind training) in compassion and wisdom
Contemplative ethics, integrating daily life with spiritual insight
His Bodhicaryāvatāra is frequently quoted by masters like the Dalai Lama, who calls it “one of my most treasured texts.”
Death and Legacy
The details of Śāntideva’s death are unknown; some legends say he wandered into the forest, others that he became a realized yogi living in seclusion
His teachings remain among the most practical and poetic in the Buddhist world
He is venerated as both a philosopher and a spiritual saint
Famous Quotes“Whatever joy there is in this world comes from wishing others to be happy. Whatever suffering there is in this world comes from wanting happiness for oneself.”
“If there’s a solution, why worry? If there’s no solution, why worry?”
“All the suffering in the world comes from wanting happiness for oneself. All the happiness in the world comes from wanting happiness for others.”`,
    shortStory: `The Story of Śāntideva
The Monk Who Walked the Way of Compassion
At the great monastery of Nālandā, where thousands of monks debated philosophy and recited sutras, there lived one monk who seemed to do nothing at all. His name was Śāntideva.
He ate. He slept. He walked quietly. He spoke little. The others called him lazy. “He contributes nothing,” they said.
But Śāntideva smiled. And listened.
One day, they asked him to give a public teaching—half as a test, half as a joke.
Śāntideva nodded. He climbed the teaching seat and asked,
“Shall I recite what is known… or what has never been heard?”
They laughed. “Something new.”
He closed his eyes.
And then he spoke.
Verse after verse flowed from him—not cold theory, but words warm with compassion and burning with truth. He spoke of the bodhisattva, who lives not for himself but for the suffering of others. He spoke of the emptiness of ego, the power of patience, the need for courageous love.
He said:
“All the happiness of the world comes from wishing others to be happy.”
“All the suffering comes from making ourselves the center.”
Some say he rose into the sky as he spoke. Others say he disappeared. But all who heard him were changed.
His words became the Bodhicaryāvatāra, a guidebook for hearts that want to serve.
And though Śāntideva faded from view, his voice never left.
It still echoes today—in every quiet act of kindness, in every monk who bows before suffering, in every seeker who dares to ask:
“What if my life was not for me… but for all?”`,
