    shortStory: `The Story of Boethius
The Philosopher Who Found Freedom in a Prison Cell
Once, in the crumbling shadow of the Roman Empire, there lived a man named Boethius—noble by birth, brilliant in mind, and loyal in heart. He served kings, read the ancients, and believed in justice, even when others forgot it.
He rose high in the Gothic court, trusted and respected. But truth, when spoken boldly, often makes enemies.
One day, for defending a friend, Boethius was accused of treason. Stripped of honors, he was thrown into a cold cell in Pavia, awaiting execution. His fortune gone, his reputation stained, his life nearly over—what did he do?
He began to write.
In the stillness of prison, a figure came to him in his mind—Lady Philosophy, robed in light, her eyes full of compassion and reason.
“Do you think Fortune betrayed you?” she asked.
“She was never yours to begin with.”
Together, they spoke of fate, freedom, virtue, and God. Boethius asked why the wicked prosper, why good men suffer, why the world turns so cruelly.
Lady Philosophy answered gently:
“True happiness lies not in power or wealth, but in the peace of a soul turned toward wisdom.”
And there, in the darkness of a dungeon, Boethius found the light of truth—not in escape, but in understanding.
Soon after, he was executed.
But his book, The Consolation of Philosophy, lived on. It passed from monk to king, from scholar to poet, whispering its truths through the centuries:
“Nothing is miserable unless you think it so.”
“The wheel of Fortune turns—but the wise are not chained to it.”
And so, Boethius, who lost everything, gave the world something greater:
A reminder that even in despair, wisdom can console,
And even in death, truth endures.`,
